Additional ggplot customization

Sample ggplot code:

library(tidyverse) # loads tidyverse
data("msleep") # loads built-in dataset into R envt

ggplot(msleep, aes(x = sleep_total, y = sleep_rem)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot between total and REM sleep",
       x = "Total amount of sleep (in hours)",
       y = "Total REM sleep (in hours)")

Noteworthy further customizations: Consider the use of theme_minimal() or theme_bw() customizations in your future data visualizations. Not required for this course.

R Workflow: Assignment Operator

In lecture 1, we discussed performing basic operations (e.g., arithmetic, logical).

Now, let us introduce the idea of assignment operators (<-), which allows you to save data in your R environment. We generally refer to saved information in your R environment as R objects.

For example, running the script below would create a variable called multiplication_example in your R environment:

multiplication_example <- 2*3

In effect, the right side of the code calculates a value (here, 2*3 = 6), then assigns/saves that value as multiplication_example in your R environment.


Printing data from your R environment

Running an R script using variable names (e.g., multiplication_example we created previously) saved within your R environment would print the contained data.

Running multiplication_example as an R script below would print the contained data:

multiplication_example 
## [1] 6


Saving values for later use

You may save values as variables or R objects.

Earlier code:

first_value <- 9
second_value <- 5 * 2

Later code:

first_value + second_value
## [1] 19


Case sensitivity

Please note the variables saved in R are case-sensitive. Earlier, we created multiplication_example.

Attempting to run MULTIPLICATION_EXAMPLE in an R script or R chunk would give you the following R error message:

MULTIPLICATION_EXAMPLE
## Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'MULTIPLICATION_EXAMPLE' not found



Note: The lecture slides cut off the entire error message which in full states: Error: object MULTIPLICATION_EXAMPLE not found


Convention: Naming R Objects

R object names must start with a letter. And may contain additional letters, numbers, _ (underscore), and . (period).

For example, here are examples of allowed object names, though not necessarily best practices, in R:

  • i_use_snake_case

  • otherPeopleUseCamelCase

  • some.people.use.periods

  • And_aFew.People_RENOUNCEconvention


Convention: Naming R Objects

Convention and best practices in R I expect you to use:

Although examples above demonstrated what is allowed, we follow a commonly accepted convention within the R community.

  • For R objects created by assignment operator (i.e., <-) into the R environment, you should only use lowercase letters, numbers, and _ (underscore).

  • Use _ (underscore) to separate words within a name (e.g., nebraska_flights).

  • Make sure your variable/object name is meaningful. For example, if the data you want to save in your R environment pertains to cancer patient data, saving the data as cancer_patient in your R environment could be an excellent choice.


Functions

A function is a block of code which only runs when it is called. They generally do meaningful jobs. You typically call functions using this format:

function_name(argument1 = value1, argument2 = value2, ...)

Although functions is barely covered in Chapter 2 of your textbook, we have used many functions already.

For example, head() is a function from base R (meaning it is built-in with R). glimpse() is another function from one of the tidyverse packages.


Functions: Arguments

As shown in the previous slides, functions can accept multiple arguments:

function_name(argument1 = value1, argument2 = value2, ...)

We previously used head() before to print a sample of our data. For example, weve run the following scripts:

Functions: Arguments

Let us pay attention to the first two arguments and the order they are shown.

Figure 2. First two arguments accepted by head().

Here is an example script where you specifically asks head() to print only the first two rows of the diamonds data:

head(x = diamonds, n = 2)
## # A tibble: 2  10
##   carat cut     color clarity depth table price     x     y     z
##   <dbl> <ord>   <ord> <ord>   <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  0.23 Ideal   E     SI2      61.5    55   326  3.95  3.98  2.43
## 2  0.21 Premium E     SI1      59.8    61   326  3.89  3.84  2.31


Functions: Arguments

Now ask yourself, why did head(diamonds) work previously in previous classes?

AGAIN: Let us pay attention to the first two arguments and the order they are shown within the documentation.

Since x (which accepts the R object data saved within your R envt) is the first argument within the arguments list from the documentation, R assumes that by running head(diamonds), you want R to assume that you want to feed diamonds into x since x is the first argument within the documentation.

The order of the arguments in the documentation matters.

Running head(diamonds, 2) is equivalent to running head(x = diamonds, n = 2). The same idea holds: since you listed 2 as the second argument within head(diamonds, 2), R will assign the value to the second argument from the documentation which is n.
